items.solution:
### Setup and Definitions

Let $X=\{a,b,c,d\}$ and $\mathcal{T}=\{\emptyset,\{a\},\{a,b\},\{a,b,c\},\{b,c,d\},X\}$. A topology must contain $\emptyset$ and $X$, be closed under arbitrary unions, and be closed under finite intersections.

### Solution

The collection violates finite intersections: $\{a,b,c\},\{b,c,d\}\in\mathcal{T}$ but $\{a,b,c\}\cap\{b,c,d\}=\{b,c\}
otin\mathcal{T}$. Hence it is not a topology. A valid proper non-discrete extension is $\mathcal{T}'=\{\emptyset,\{a\},\{b\},\{a,b\},\{b,c\},\{a,b,c\},\{b,c,d\},X\}$. Its unions and finite intersections remain in the list, it contains $\mathcal{T}$, and $\{c\}
otin\mathcal{T}'$, so it is not discrete.

items.statement:
Let 𝑋 be a non-empty set, and let 𝑥0 be an element of 𝑋. Show that
 = {𝑈 ⊆ 𝑋 ∣ 𝑥0 ∉ 𝑈 or 𝑋 ⧵ 𝑈 is finite}
is a topology on 𝑋.

Show that
 = {(𝑎, ∞) ∣ 𝑎 ∈ ℝ} ∪ {(−∞, 𝑏) ∣ 𝑏 ∈ ℝ}
is a subbasis for the standard topology on ℝ.
